Preheat your #oven{} to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9.

Chop the @sweet potato{1} into 1cm chunks (no need to peel). Pop onto a
#baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil for cooking{1%tbsp}, season with @salt{} and
@black pepper{}, then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden and tender,
~{16-18%mins}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Halve the @lime{1/2}.

Drain and rinse the @lentils{1%carton} in a #sieve{}.

Cut the @paneer{226%grams} into 1cm cubes. Heat the oil in a #frying pan{}
on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the paneer to the pan, season with salt and pepper. Fry until
golden all over, ~{5-8%mins}. Turn regularly to brown them evenly.

Add the garlic and @pasanda style seasoning{1%sachet}. Cook, stirring, for
~{1%min}.

Add the @coconut milk{180%milliliters}, @vegetable stock paste{10%grams} and
@water{50%milliliters} to the paneer. Mix well, then add the lentils.

Bring to the boil, stir, then lower the heat so the sauce simmers gently,
~{8-10%mins}.

Add the @baby spinach{40%grams} to the curry a handful at a time until wilted
and piping hot, ~{1-2%mins}.

Once the sweet potato is cooked, add to the curry with a squeeze of lime juice.

Taste and season if needed, adding a splash of water if it's a little dry.

Share the lentil and paneer curry between your bowls.

Serve with any remaining lime cut into wedges for squeezing over. Enjoy!